An Introduction to the Tidyverse

Session Two Solutions

As always, we start by loading the tidyverse package.

library(tidyverse)

Coding Basics

R as a Calculator 1

Part 1

# notice that we don't have to use `to =` and `from = `
# since these parameters can be recognised by postiion
integers <- seq(0, 100)

Part 2

squares <- integers ^ 2

Part 3

squares_df <- tibble(integers, squares)

Lets have a look at the first four rows of squares_df just to make sure that everything is as expected.

head(squares_df, n = 4)

Part 4

# no need to specify `data =` or `mapping =`
ggplot(squares_df) +
  geom_point(aes(x = integers, y = squares))

R as a calculator

Part 1

x <- seq(-6, 6, length.out = 1000)

NB: Another interesting parameter of seq is by = which determines what gap should be between each value in the sequence.

Part 2

# note - R uses radians!
y <- sin(x)

Part 3

# you can call this whatever you want
sin_df <- tibble(x, y)

Part 4

ggplot(sin_df) +
  geom_line(aes(x = x, y = y), col = 'orange', linetype = 2, size = 1.5)

Specifying Parameters by Position

Part 1

data and mapping are perhaps the most obvious ones but it turns out that you can actually remove x = and y = too (though in my personal opinion, it is unclear to do so). colour = must be specified though.

Reading CSVs

Remember to set your working directory first with Session > Set Working Directory... in the top bar of RStudio

The People Dataset

Part 1

people <- read_csv('data/people.csv', 
                   col_types = cols(
                     sex = col_factor(),
                     race = col_factor(),
                     earn = col_integer(),
                     age = col_integer()
                   ))

Part 2

ggplot(people) +
  geom_point(aes(x = ed, y = earn), position = 'jitter', alpha = 0.5)

It appears that increasing education is weakly correlated with earnings up to education level 12 (TODO: what does this represent) although after this point, increasing education doesnt seem to have much affect on typical earnings although it does appear to unlock access to many high paid jobs.

Part 3

ggplot(people) +
  geom_point(aes(x = ed, y = earn, col = sex), position = 'jitter', alpha = 0.5, show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sex)

Part 4

ggplot(people) +
  geom_point(aes(x = ed, y = earn, col = sex), position = 'jitter', alpha = 0.5, show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sex)  +
  labs(x = 'Level of Education',
       y = 'Earnings',
       title = 'A plot showing the relationship between earnings and education level',
       subtitle = 'Split by sex')

Part 5

ggplot(people) +
  geom_smooth(aes(x = age, y = earn))

Part 6

ggplot(people) +
  geom_smooth(aes(x = age, y = earn, col = race), size = 2)

NB: Here error bars are useful. It appears from the smoothed curve alone that being a race other than white, black, or Hispanic may relate to having large earnings later in life. This pattern is most likely due to a single outlier. We can spot this because the errors on the other curve are very large for high age, signifying uncertainly in the curves position.

Part 4

I will also colour this line red to distinguish it from the rest of the data.

# aesthetics placed here so that they are inherited by both geometries
ggplot(weather, aes(x = date, y = mean_temp)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(col = 'red', se = FALSE)

Part 5

ggplot(weather, aes(x = mean_cloud, y = total_rainfall)) +
  geom_point(position = 'jitter')

It appears that more cloud does not necessarily mean more rain but is often a requirement for a lot of rain.

  labs(x = 'Cloud Coverage (Proportion of Sky)')

Part 4

There are a few ways to do this depending on which parameters you use for read_fwf(). I will use the named column positions approach. See ?read_fwf for more details.

read_fwf('data/beijing_may_oct_1987.txt',
         skip = 6,
         na = 'n/a',
         col_positions = fwf_cols(
           date = c(2, 11),
           temperature = c(14, 24),
           rainfall = c(27, 34),
           pressure = c(39, 46),
           wind_speed = c(49, 58),
           beaufort = c(63, 70)
         ))

Line Geometries

Groups

Part 1

There are many methods we can use to learn more about this dataset - str(), summary(), head(), names, etc. But I will use ?ChickWeight. This contains detailed descriptions of the columns.

Part 2

ggplot(ChickWeight) +
  geom_line(aes(x = Time, y = weight, col = Diet, group = Chick))

Part 3

You get a mess:

ggplot(ChickWeight) +
  geom_line(aes(x = Time, y = weight, col = Diet))

Here the data from all chicks on the same diet is collected into a single line and so at each unit of time where we measured weight, we get a vertical line, representing multiple measurements.

Part 4

ggplot(ChickWeight) +
  geom_smooth(aes(x = Time, y = weight, col = Diet), se = FALSE)

We dont need to specify grouping since geom_smooth() is designed to take all data and combine it together to form a summary.

Part 5

ggplot(ChickWeight, aes(x = Time, y = weight, col = Diet)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  geom_point(position = 'jitter', alpha = 0.5)

Part 6

Using ?ChickWeight will help us a lot here

ggplot(ChickWeight, aes(x = Time, y = weight, col = Diet)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  geom_point(position = 'jitter', alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(x = 'Days since birth',
       y = 'Weight (g)',
       col = 'Diet',
       title = 'A plot showing the weight changes of chicks on four different diets')

Smoothing Methods

Part 1

ggplot(iris) +
  geom_point(aes(x = Sepal.Width, y = Sepal.Length, col = Species))

Part 2

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Width, y = Sepal.Length, col = Species)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = 'lm')

Part 3

Well look at LOESS since GAMs are generally more applicable to larger datasets

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Width, y = Sepal.Length, col = Species)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = 'loess')

Part 4

The default for small datasets is LOESS and for large it is GAMs. This dataset is small so geom_smooth uses LOESS.

Going Beyond

Theming Graphs

Part 1

I will make a plot of highway mileage vs city mileage

ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_point(aes(x = hwy, y = cty))

Part 2

ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_point(aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  labs(x = 'Highway Mileage',
       y = 'City Mileage',
       title = 'A graph comparing city and highway mileage for various cars')

Part 3

ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_point(aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  labs(x = 'Highway Mileage',
       y = 'City Mileage',
       title = 'A graph comparing city and highway mileage for various cars') +
  theme_minimal()

Part 4

Another theme I like is theme_bw() which is an understated black and white design.

ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_point(aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  labs(x = 'Highway Mileage',
       y = 'City Mileage',
       title = 'A graph comparing city and highway mileage for various cars') +
  theme_bw()
